We don't rewrite URLs, so these are useless and can confuse search engines.

See http://randomcoder.com/articles/jsessionid-considered-harmful

Thumbnailing attachments does not provide error checking for incompatible file types:

Thumbnails.java Line 50: 
{noformat}
if (!thumbnailManager.isThumbnailable(attachment))
                continue;
{noformat}

AbstractThumbnailManager Line 153:
{noformat}
public boolean isThumbnailable(Attachment attachment)
    {
        String contentType = FileTypeUtil.getContentType(attachment.getFileName());
        return Thumber.THUMBNAIL_MIME_TYPES.contains(contentType);
    }
{noformat}

After attaching a pdf file to a page's attachments and using the display image and thumbnail wiki markup with the PDF attachment 
{noformat}!export.pdf|thumbnail!{noformat}

 caused the Browser to hang after the page content began loading.  The browser had to be killed, else it would remain frozen.

There is no warning in Confluence stating that the invalid syntax is used. Additionally, the code above shows that it will simply continue if it is not of the supported formats. 
Perhaps it would be a good idea to include error messages when invalid syntax is used?

1. Create a page in wiki markup:
{code}
h1. heading
{children}
h1. heading
{code}

2. Save, and edit in wysiwyg.
4. Switch to wiki view and the markup is now:

{code}
h1. heading

{children}

h1. heading
{code}

3. Save, and edit again in wyswyg
4. Switch to wiki and the markup is now
{code}
h1. heading

{children}\\
h1. heading
{code}

5. Edit again, in wysiwyg, and save. The markup is now:
{code}
h1. heading

\\
{children}\\
\\
\\
h1. heading
{code}

This adding of whitespace is quite annoying when you are editing a document multiple times, and you have to keep deleting the blank lines added.

When bold wiki markup ending with a hyperlink is saved, it is rendered without the bold typeface and incorrectly displays the * markup characters. 

To replicate, paste the following wiki markup into a page:
{noformat}
*Bold Text http://www.google.com*
*http://www.google.com*
{noformat}

